Note:
==============================================================================
CIE 1931 XYZ - Device-Independent Tristimulus Reference
==============================================================================

The CIE 1931 XYZ color space (CIE Publication 15:2004, "Colorimetry, 3rd
Edition", and the original 1931 standard reproduced in
G. Wyszecki and W. S. Stiles, "Color Science: Concepts and Methods,
Quantitative Data and Formulae", 2nd ed., Wiley 1982) is the canonical
device-independent reference space against which every other colour
space transformation is defined.

XYZ tristimulus values represent the integral of a spectral power
distribution against the 2-degree CIE 1931 standard observer's three
colour-matching functions x_bar(lambda), y_bar(lambda), z_bar(lambda).
By construction:
  Y is the luminance (photometric brightness).
  X and Z carry the chromatic information.
  All real (non-imaginary) colours have non-negative XYZ.
  The xy chromaticity coordinates derive as
       x = X / (X+Y+Z), y = Y / (X+Y+Z), z = 1 - x - y.

This module exposes:
  - The XYZ struct (Float64 fields x, y, z, normalised so that the
    reference white maps to Y = 1.0 in the unit-Y convention).
  - The standard CIE illuminants (D65, D50, D55, D75, A, C, E) for use
    by lab.runa (CIELAB / CIELCh / CIELUV) and color_space.runa.
  - Linear-RGB <-> XYZ matrix transforms for the sRGB / BT.709 primaries
    (IEC 61966-2-1:1999, Recommendation ITU-R BT.709-6).

The chromatic adaptation matrices (Bradford, von Kries, CAT02) live in
color_space.runa; this module supplies only the canonical primaries.

References:
  - CIE Publication 15:2004 "Colorimetry, 3rd Edition"
  - IEC 61966-2-1:1999 (sRGB encoding)
  - ITU-R BT.709-6 (Parameter values for the HDTV standards)
  - G. Wyszecki and W. S. Stiles, "Color Science", Wiley 1982
==============================================================================
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "XYZ":
    x as Float
    y as Float
    z as Float
End Type

Type called "WhitePoint":
    x as Float
    y as Float
    z as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STANDARD CIE ILLUMINANT WHITE POINTS (Y normalised to 1.0)
Note: Per CIE 15:2004 Table T.3, 2-degree observer
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "white_point_d65" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    Return the CIE D65 daylight illuminant tristimulus, the reference
    white for sRGB, BT.709, BT.2020, AdobeRGB, and DisplayP3. Values
    are sourced from CIE 15:2004 Table T.3, 2-degree observer, with
    Y normalised to 1.0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Hard-coded constants exactly matching the published CIE source
    (X = 0.95047, Y = 1.00000, Z = 1.08883).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 0.95047
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 1.08883
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_d50" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    Return the CIE D50 horizon-light illuminant tristimulus, the reference
    white for ICC profile interchange and ProPhotoRGB. Values from
    CIE 15:2004 Table T.3.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Hard-coded constants (X = 0.96422, Y = 1.00000, Z = 0.82521).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 0.96422
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 0.82521
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_d55" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    CIE D55 mid-morning / mid-afternoon daylight illuminant (5500K), used
    as the reference white for some legacy photographic standards.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    X = 0.95682, Y = 1.00000, Z = 0.92149 per CIE 15:2004.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 0.95682
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 0.92149
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_d75" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    CIE D75 north-sky daylight illuminant (7500K), used in some calibration
    contexts that benchmark colder daylight than D65.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    X = 0.94972, Y = 1.00000, Z = 1.22638 per CIE 15:2004.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 0.94972
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 1.22638
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_a" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    CIE Standard Illuminant A: incandescent tungsten 2856K. Reference for
    legacy indoor photography evaluation per ISO 7589.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    X = 1.09850, Y = 1.00000, Z = 0.35585 per CIE 15:2004.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 1.09850
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 0.35585
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_c" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    CIE Standard Illuminant C: average daylight 6774K, the original NTSC
    1953 reference white (now superseded by D65 in BT.709).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    X = 0.98074, Y = 1.00000, Z = 1.18232 per CIE 15:2004.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 0.98074
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 1.18232
    Return w
End Process

Process called "white_point_e" returns WhitePoint:
    @Reasoning
    CIE Illuminant E (equal-energy): uniform radiator. Useful as a
    theoretical reference where chromatic adaptation is intentionally
    absent.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    X = 1.00000, Y = 1.00000, Z = 1.00000 by definition.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three constant loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure constant.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let w be a value of type WhitePoint
    Set w.x to 1.00000
    Set w.y to 1.00000
    Set w.z to 1.00000
    Return w
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XYZ CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "xyz_create" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns XYZ:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a CIE 1931 XYZ tristimulus value. No clamping is performed
    because wide-gamut spaces (ProPhotoRGB, ACES) routinely carry XYZ
    values that fall outside the spectral locus once the matrix transform
    completes.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct field assignment.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be a value of type XYZ
    Set v.x to x
    Set v.y to y
    Set v.z to z
    Return v
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: sRGB / BT.709 LINEAR RGB <-> XYZ TRANSFORMS (D65 WHITE POINT)
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Matrix per IEC 61966-2-1:1999 Annex A and ITU-R BT.709-6:

 X      0.4124564   0.3575761   0.1804375   R_linear
 Y  =   0.2126729   0.7151522   0.0721750   G_linear
 Z      0.0193339   0.1191920   0.9503041   B_linear

Inverse (XYZ -> linear-sRGB):

 R       3.2404542  -1.5371385  -0.4985314  X
 G  =   -0.9692660   1.8760108   0.0415560  Y
 B       0.0556434  -0.2040259   1.0572252  Z
:End Note

Process called "linear_srgb_to_xyz_d65" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns XYZ:
    @Reasoning
    Convert linear sRGB (NOT gamma-encoded) channel values to CIE 1931
    XYZ under the D65 reference white. The forward matrix is fixed by
    IEC 61966-2-1:1999 Annex A and is identical to the BT.709-6 matrix.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Three dot products of the input vector against each row of the
    forward matrix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Nine multiplies + six adds. About 3 ns on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be a value of type XYZ
    Set v.x to ((r multiplied by 0.4124564) plus (g multiplied by 0.3575761)) plus (b multiplied by 0.1804375)
    Set v.y to ((r multiplied by 0.2126729) plus (g multiplied by 0.7151522)) plus (b multiplied by 0.0721750)
    Set v.z to ((r multiplied by 0.0193339) plus (g multiplied by 0.1191920)) plus (b multiplied by 0.9503041)
    Return v
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_linear_srgb_r" takes v as XYZ returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Return the linear-sRGB red channel from an XYZ tristimulus under
    D65 reference white. Used as one of three results when callers prefer
    discrete-channel returns over a struct.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Dot product of v with the first row of the inverse matrix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies + two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((v.x multiplied by 3.2404542) plus (v.y multiplied by 0.0 minus 1.5371385)) plus (v.z multiplied by 0.0 minus 0.4985314)
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_linear_srgb_g" takes v as XYZ returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Return the linear-sRGB green channel from an XYZ tristimulus.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Dot product of v with the second row of the inverse matrix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies + two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((v.x multiplied by 0.0 minus 0.9692660) plus (v.y multiplied by 1.8760108)) plus (v.z multiplied by 0.0415560)
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_linear_srgb_b" takes v as XYZ returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Return the linear-sRGB blue channel from an XYZ tristimulus.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Dot product of v with the third row of the inverse matrix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies + two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((v.x multiplied by 0.0556434) plus (v.y multiplied by 0.0 minus 0.2040259)) plus (v.z multiplied by 1.0572252)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHROMATICITY (xyY representation)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "xyz_to_chromaticity_x" takes v as XYZ returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Compute the CIE 1931 chromaticity x coordinate from a tristimulus:
        x = X / (X + Y + Z)
    Returns 0.0 when the input has zero sum to avoid divide-by-zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two adds + one divide. Guard against zero sum.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sum be (v.x plus v.y) plus v.z
    If sum is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Return v.x divided by sum
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_chromaticity_y" takes v as XYZ returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Compute the CIE 1931 chromaticity y coordinate: y = Y / (X + Y + Z).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two adds + one divide.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sum be (v.x plus v.y) plus v.z
    If sum is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Return v.y divided by sum
End Process

Process called "chromaticity_to_xyz" takes chx as Float, chy as Float, big_y as Float returns XYZ:
    @Reasoning
    Recover an XYZ tristimulus from its chromaticity (x, y) and luminance
    Y. Standard formulation:
        X = (x / y) * Y       Y = Y       Z = ((1 - x - y) / y) * Y
    Returns the origin when y is non-positive to avoid divide-by-zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    One subtract, three divides, two multiplies.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be a value of type XYZ
    If chy is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Set v.x to 0.0
        Set v.y to 0.0
        Set v.z to 0.0
        Return v
    End If
    Set v.x to (chx divided by chy) multiplied by big_y
    Set v.y to big_y
    Let z_norm be 1.0 minus (chx plus chy)
    Set v.z to (z_norm divided by chy) multiplied by big_y
    Return v
End Process

Process called "xyz_add" takes a as XYZ, b as XYZ returns XYZ:
    @Reasoning
    Componentwise addition. Used internally by chromatic-adaptation
    derivations and weighted averaging of XYZ palettes.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Three adds.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type XYZ
    Set out.x to a.x plus b.x
    Set out.y to a.y plus b.y
    Set out.z to a.z plus b.z
    Return out
End Process

Process called "xyz_scale" takes v as XYZ, s as Float returns XYZ:
    @Reasoning
    Multiply each component by a scalar. Used to normalise XYZ to a
    target luminance.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Three multiplies.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type XYZ
    Set out.x to v.x multiplied by s
    Set out.y to v.y multiplied by s
    Set out.z to v.z multiplied by s
    Return out
End Process
